Followups to talk.politics.crypto; this doesn't belong in sci.crypt.

In article <WCS.94May13022235@anchor.ATT.COM> wcs@anchor.ho.att.com (Bill Stewart +1-510-484-6204) writes:
> Even if your encryption system is *not* very good, it cannot legally be
> exported without government permission, unless you have enough lawyers
> to support a case that public-domain software may be exportable
> (risking 10 years in jail if you lose.)

False. The literal language of USML XIII(b)(1) is limited to crypto
``with the capability of maintaining secrecy or confidentiality of 
information or information systems.'' Poor crypto doesn't have that
capability.

---Dan
